<br>
Robert Forrest (Letters, 17 August) seems to be helping make my pro-nuclear case for me when he writes that nuclear plants &quot;sell cheap power at night&quot;, although his assertion that Ben Cruachan's 500 mega-watt output &quot;is not a source of generation&quot; seems confused, to say the least. <br>
<br>
His statement that &quot;many renewable energy sources are intermittent&quot; is, however, again accurate, as chronic intermittency is a principal characteristic of wind turbines. The average output of a turbine would boil about 40 electric kettles, and it would take just under 1,000 on a windy night in over 200 large wind farms to pump the water back up from Loch Awe to the top of Ben Cruachan. <br>
<br>
Interaction of generating capacity depends substanti-ally on nuclear capacity, and always will. <br>
<br>
In its anti-nuclear zeal, the green cult ignores the huge environmental consequences of wind farms. The Ovenden Moor wind farm in Yorkshire has cracked the bedrock and diver-ted natural watercourses. Along cable trenches, the thin layers of peat are drying out rapidly and blowing away. Tracks to and between turbines have acted as dams, and formed deep pools of fetid surface water that cannot drain away. <br>
<br>
This has contributed to the formidable and substantially successful determination in Yorkshire and the north of England to oppose these developments, and the consequent attempts by companies such as Powergen to foist them on Scotland. It's an auld sang, is it not? <br>
<br>
ALAN CLAYTON <br>
